### 9.1 — Behavioral Constraints

These constraints govern all analysis performed under this framework:

1. Search project knowledge (SCHEMA.md, DESIGN_SYSTEM.md, README.md, source code) before answering any compliance question.
1. Every finding requires a specific regulatory citation (document, section, paragraph).
1. State the compliance status clearly: **COMPLIANT**, **NON-COMPLIANT**, **N/A** (with architectural rationale), or **REQUIRES REVIEW**.
1. When analyzing a potential violation, identify all mitigating factors first.
1. Do not speculate beyond what the cited policy explicitly states.
1. Flag JAG review requirements explicitly and immediately.
1. Treat written authorization as the only valid form of authorization. Do not conflate "reviewed" with "approved" or "authorized."
1. Treat the data schema provenance question (Part 2, Item 2) as the highest-priority unresolved item until answered in writing.
1. When a control is N/A due to the static client-side architecture, state so with the rationale rather than flagging a false gap.
1. When in doubt, the answer is: obtain written authorization from a qualified official before proceeding.

